443 /**

4004 /**
4005 Wait until the subject share is removed from the table
4006 definition cache and make sure it's destroyed.
4007
4008 @note This method may access the share concurrently with another
4009 thread if the share is in the process of being opened, i.e., that
4010 m_open_in_progress is true. In this case, close_cached_tables() may
4011 iterate over elements in the table definition cache, and call this
4012 method regardless of the share being opened or not. This works anyway
4013 since a new flush ticket is added below, and LOCK_open ensures
4014 that the share may not be destroyed by another thread in the time
4015 between finding this share (having an old version) and adding the flush
4016 ticket. Thus, after this thread has added the flush ticket, the thread
4017 opening the table will eventually call free_table_share (as a result of
4018 releasing the share after using it, or as a result of a failing
4019 open_table_def()), which will notify the owners of the flush tickets,
4020 and the last one being notified will actually destroy the share.
4021
4022 @param thd Session.
4023 @param abstime Timeout for waiting as absolute time value.
4024 @param deadlock_weight Weight of this wait for deadlock detector.
4025
4026 @pre LOCK_open is write locked, the share is used (has
4027 non-zero reference count), is marked for flush and
4028 this connection does not reference the share.
4029 LOCK_open will be unlocked temporarily during execution.
4030
4031 @retval false - Success.

5320 natural/using join.
5321

5323 @param parent_table_ref the parent table reference over which the
5324 iterator is iterating
5325

5327 iterator if no such column was created, or return an already
5328 created natural join column. The former happens for base tables or
5329 views, and the latter for natural/using joins. If a new field is
5330 created, then the field is added to 'parent_table_ref' if it is
5331 given, or to the original table reference of the field if
5332 parent_table_ref == NULL.

5335 This method is designed so that when a Field_iterator_table_ref
5336 walks through the fields of a table reference, all its fields
5337 are created and stored as follows:

5686 /**

5692 build a complete row). If this is the case, we mark all not
5693 updated columns to be read.
5694

5696 if needed, either the primary key column or all columns to be read.

5698

5700 mark all USED key columns as 'to-be-read'. This allows the engine to
5701 loop over the given record to find all changed keys and doesn't have to
5702 retrieve the row again.
5703
5704 Unlike other similar methods, it doesn't mark fields used by triggers,
5705 that is the responsibility of the caller to do, by using
5706 Table_trigger_dispatcher::mark_used_fields(TRG_EVENT_UPDATE)!
5707

5709 influence query execution plan. For example in the case of
5710 binlog_row_image=FULL the entire read_set and write_set needs to be flagged.
5711 This will influence update query to think that 'used key is being modified'
5712 and query will create a temporary table to process the update operation.
5713 Which will result in performance degradation. Hence callers who don't want
5714 their query execution to be influenced as per binlog_row_image requirements
5715 can skip marking binlog specific columns here and they should make an
5716 explicit call to 'mark_columns_per_binlog_row_image()' function to mark

5761 /*
5762 Mark columns according the binlog row image option.
5763
5764 When logging in RBR, the user can select whether to
5765 log partial or full rows, depending on the table
5766 definition, and the value of binlog_row_image.
5767
5768 Semantics of the binlog_row_image are the following
5769 (PKE - primary key equivalent, ie, PK fields if PK
5770 exists, all fields otherwise):
5771
5772 binlog_row_image= MINIMAL
5773 - This marks the PKE fields in the read_set
5774 - This marks all fields where a value was specified
5775 in the write_set
5776
5777 binlog_row_image= NOBLOB
5778 - This marks PKE + all non-blob fields in the read_set
5779 - This marks all fields where a value was specified
5780 and all non-blob fields in the write_set
5781
5782 binlog_row_image= FULL

5787 bitmaps. This means that we will strip extra fields in

5845 /**

5847
5848 @param new_key_count Number of wanted keys.

5856 but generally, only a few keys are needed. Notice that no or little
5857 extra allocation is required for repeated executions, as one optimization
5858 is able to reuse space allocated in the previous optimization.
5859
5860 When modifying TABLE, modifications to TABLE_SHARE are needed, so that both
5861 objects remain consistent. Even if several TABLEs point to the same
5862 TABLE_SHARE, those modifications must be done only once (consider for
5863 example, incremementing TABLE_SHARE::keys). Should they be done when
5864 processing the first TABLE, or the second, or? In case this function, when
5865 updating TABLE, relies on TABLE_SHARE members which are the subject of
5866 modifications, we follow this rule: do those TABLE_SHARE member
5867 modifications first: thus, TABLE-modifying code can be identical for all
5868 TABLEs. So the _first_ TABLE calling this function, only, should pass
5869 'true': all next ones should not modify the TABLE_SHARE.
5870
5871 @returns false if success, true if error
5872 */
5873

6239 /**
6240 @brief Update the write/read_set for generated columns
6241 when doing update and insert operation.
6242
6243 @param is_update true means the operation is UPDATE.
6244 false means it's INSERT.
6245
6246
6247 Prerequisites for INSERT:
6248
6249 - write_map is filled with all base columns.
6250
6251 - read_map is filled with base columns and generated columns to be read.
6252 Otherwise, it is empty. covering_keys and merge_keys are adjusted according
6253 to read_map.
6254
6255 Actions for INSERT:
6256
6257 - Fill write_map with all generated columns.
6258 Stored columns are needed because their values will be stored.
6259 Virtual columns are needed because their values must be checked against
6260 constraints and it might be referenced by latter generated columns.
6261
6262 - Fill read_map with base columns for all generated columns.
6263 This has no technical reason, but is required because the function that
6264 evaluates generated functions asserts that base columns are in the read_map.
6265 covering_keys and merge_keys are adjusted according to read_map.
6266
6267 Prerequisites for UPDATE:
6268
6269 - write_map is filled with base columns to be updated.
6270
6271 - read_map is filled with base columns and generated columns to be read
6272 prior to the row update. covering_keys and merge_keys are adjusted
6273 according to read_map.
6274
6275 Actions for UPDATE:
6276
6277 - Fill write_map with generated columns that are dependent on updated base
6278 columns and all virtual generated columns. Stored columns are needed because
6279 their values will be stored. Virtual columns are needed because their values
6280 must be checked against constraints and might be referenced by latter
6281 generated columns.
6282 */

6389 /**
6390 Compiles the tagged hints list and fills up the bitmasks.
6391
6392 @param thd The current session.
6393 @param tbl the TABLE to operate on.
6394
6395 The parser collects the index hints for each table in a "tagged list"
6396 (TABLE_LIST::index_hints). Using the information in this tagged list
6397 this function sets the members st_table::keys_in_use_for_query,
6398 st_table::keys_in_use_for_group_by, st_table::keys_in_use_for_order_by,
6399 st_table::force_index, st_table::force_index_order,
6400 st_table::force_index_group and st_table::covering_keys.
6401
6402 Current implementation of the runtime does not allow mixing FORCE INDEX
6403 and USE INDEX, so this is checked here. Then the FORCE INDEX list
6404 (if non-empty) is appended to the USE INDEX list and a flag is set.
6405
6406 Multiple hints of the same kind are processed so that each clause
6407 is applied to what is computed in the previous clause.
6408 For example:
6409 USE INDEX (i1) USE INDEX (i2)
6410 is equivalent to
6411 USE INDEX (i1,i2)
6412 and means "consider only i1 and i2".
6413
6414 Similarly
6415 USE INDEX () USE INDEX (i1)
6416 is equivalent to
6417 USE INDEX (i1)
6418 and means "consider only the index i1"
6419
6420 It is OK to have the same index several times, e.g. "USE INDEX (i1,i1)" is
6421 not an error.
6422
6423 Different kind of hints (USE/FORCE/IGNORE) are processed in the following
6424 order:
6425 1. All indexes in USE (or FORCE) INDEX are added to the mask.
6426 2. All IGNORE INDEX
6427
6428 e.g. "USE INDEX i1, IGNORE INDEX i1, USE INDEX i1" will not use i1 at all
6429 as if we had "USE INDEX i1, USE INDEX i1, IGNORE INDEX i1".
6430
6431 @retval false No errors found.
6432 @retval true Found and reported an error.
6433 */

6652 /**
6653 A helper function to add a derived key to the list of possible keys
6654
6655 @param thd thread handler
6656 @param derived_key_list list of all possible derived keys
6657 @param field referenced field
6658 @param ref_by_tbl the table that refers to given field
6659
6660 @details The possible key to be used for join with table with ref_by_tbl
6661 table map is extended to include 'field'. If ref_by_tbl == 0 then the key
6662 that includes all referred fields is extended.
6663
6664 @note
6665 Procedure of keys generation for result tables of materialized derived
6666 tables/views for allowing ref access to them.
6667
6668 A key is generated for each equi-join pair (derived table, another table).
6669 Each generated key consists of fields of derived table used in equi-join.
6670 Example:
6671
6672 @code
6673 SELECT * FROM (SELECT f1, f2, count(*) FROM t1 GROUP BY f1) tt JOIN
6674 t1 ON tt.f1=t1.f3 and tt.f2=t1.f4;
6675 @endcode
6676
6677 In this case for the derived table tt one key will be generated. It will
6678 consist of two parts f1 and f2.
6679 Example:
6680
6681 @code
6682 SELECT * FROM (SELECT f1, f2, count(*) FROM t1 GROUP BY f1) tt JOIN
6683 t1 ON tt.f1=t1.f3 JOIN
6684 t2 ON tt.f2=t2.f4;
6685 @endcode
6686
6687 In this case for the derived table tt two keys will be generated.
6688 One key over f1 field, and another key over f2 field.
6689 Currently optimizer may choose to use only one such key, thus the second
6690 one will be dropped after the range optimizer is finished.
6691 See also JOIN::finalize_derived_keys function.
6692 Example:
6693
6694 @code
6695 SELECT * FROM (SELECT f1, f2, count(*) FROM t1 GROUP BY f1) tt JOIN
6696 t1 ON tt.f1=a_function(t1.f3);
6697 @endcode
6698
6699 In this case for the derived table tt one key will be generated. It will
6700 consist of one field - f1.
6701 In all cases beside one-per-table keys one additional key is generated.
6702 It includes all fields referenced by other tables.
6703
6704 Implementation is split in three steps:
6705
6706 1. gather information on all used fields of derived tables/view and
6707 store it in lists of possible keys, one per a derived table/view.
6708 2. add keys to result tables of derived tables/view using info from above
6709 lists.
6710 (...Planner selects best key...)
6711 3. drop unused keys from the table.
6712
6713 The above procedure is implemented in 4 functions:
6714 1. TABLE_LIST::update_derived_keys()
6715 Create/extend list of possible keys for one derived
6716 table/view based on given field/used tables info.
6717 (Step one)
6718 2. JOIN::generate_derived_keys()
6719 This function is called from update_ref_and_keys
6720 when all possible info on keys is gathered and it's
6721 safe to add keys - no keys or key parts would be
6722 missed. Walk over list of derived tables/views and
6723 call to TABLE_LIST::generate_keys to actually
6724 generate keys. (Step two)
6725 3. TABLE_LIST::generate_keys()
6726 Walks over list of possible keys for this derived
6727 table/view to add keys to the result table.
6728 Calls to TABLE::add_tmp_key() to actually add
6729 keys (i.e. KEY objects in TABLE::key_info). (Step
6730 two)
6731 4. TABLE::add_tmp_key() Creates one index description according to given
6732 bitmap of used fields. (Step two)
6733 [ Planner runs and possibly chooses one key, stored in Key_use->key ]
6734 JOIN::finalize_derived_keys Walk over list of derived tables/views to
6735 destroy unused keys. (Step three)
6736
6737 This design is used for derived tables, views and CTEs. As a CTE
6738 can be multi-referenced, some points are worth noting:
6739
6740 ## Definitions
6741
6742 - let's call the CTE 'X'
6743 - Key creation/deletion happens in a window between the start of
6744 update_derived_keys() and the end of finalize_derived_keys().
6745
6746 ## Key array locking
6747
6748 - Evaluation of constant subqueries (and thus their optimization)
6749 may happen either before, inside, or after the window above:
6750 * an example of "before": `WHERE 1=(subq))`, due to optimize_cond()
6751 * an example of "inside": `WHERE col<>(subq)`, as make_join_plan()
6752 calls estimate_rowcount() which calls the range optimizer for <>, which
6753 evaluates subq
6754 * an example of "after": `WHERE key_col=(subq)`, due to
6755 create_ref_for_key().
6756 - let's say that a being-optimized query block 'QB1' is entering that
6757 window; other query blocks are QB2, etc; let's say (subq) above is QB2, a
6758 subquery of QB1.
6759 - While QB1 is in this window, it is possible, as we saw above, that QB2
6760 gets optimized. Because it is not safe to have two query blocks
6761 reading/writing possible keys for a same table at the same time, a locking
6762 mechanism is in place: TABLE_SHARE::owner_of_possible_tmp_keys is a record
6763 of which query block entered first the window for this table and hasn't left
6764 it yet; only that query block is allowed to read/write possible keys for
6765 this table.
6766
6767 ## Key array growth
6768
6769 - let's say that a being-optimized query block 'QB1' is entering the
6770 window; other query blocks are QB2 (not necessarily the same QB2 as in
6771 previous paragraph), etc.
6772 - let's call "local" the references to X in QB1, let's call "nonlocal" the
6773 ones in other query blocks. For example,
6774
6775 @code
6776 with X(n) as (select 1)
6777 select /+ QB_NAME(QB2) *_/ n from X as X2
6778 where X2.n = (select /+* QB_NAME(QB1) *_/ X1.n from X as X1)
6779 union
6780 select n+2 from X as X3;
6781 @endcode
6782
6783 QB1 owns the window, then X1 is local, X2 and X3 are nonlocal.
6784 - when QB1 enters the window, update_derived_keys() starts for the local
6785 reference X1, other references to X may already have keys,
6786 defined by previously optimized query blocks on their
6787 references (e.g. QB2 on X2). At that stage the TABLE_SHARE::key_info array is
6788 of size TABLE_SHARE::keys, and the TABLE_SHARE::first_unused_tmp_key member
6789 points to 'where any new key should be added in this array', so it's equal
6790 to TABLE_SHARE::keys. Let's call the keys defined by QB2 the "existing
6791 keys": they exist at this point and will continue to do so. X2 in QB2 is
6792 already set up to read with such key. Here's the key_info array, with cell 0
6793 to the left, "E" meaning "an existing key, created by previous
6794 optimizations", "-" meaning "an empty cell created by alloc_keys()".
6795
6796 @verbatim
6797 EEEEEEEEEE-----------
6798 ^ s->first_unused_keys
6799 ^ s->keys
6800 @endverbatim
6801
6802 - generate_keys() extends the key_info array and adds "possible" keys to the
6803 end. "Possible" is defined as "not yet existing", "might be dropped in the
6804 end". Even if a possible key is a duplicate of an existing key, it is
6805 added. TABLE_SHARE::keys is increased to include existing and possible
6806 keys. All TABLEs referencing X, local or not, are kept in sync (i.e. any
6807 possible key is added to all key_info arrays). But possible keys are set to
6808 be unusable by nonlocal references, so that the decision to drop those keys
6809 can be left to the window's owner. Key_info array now is ("P" means
6810 "possible key"):
6811
6812 @verbatim
6813 EEEEEEEEEEPPPPPPP---
6814 ^ s->first_unused_keys
6815 ^ s->keys
6816 @endverbatim
6817
6818
6819 - All possible keys are unused, at this stage.
6820 - Planner selects the best key for each local reference, among existing and
6821 possible keys, it is recorded in Key_use.
6822 - finalize_derived_keys() looks at local references, and gathers the list
6823 of (existing and possible) keys which the Planner has chosen for them. We
6824 call this list the list of locally-used keys, marked below with "!":
6825
6826 @verbatim
6827 ! ! !
6828 EEEEEEEEEEPPPPPPP---
6829 ^ s->first_unused_keys
6830 ^ s->keys
6831 @endverbatim
6832
6833 - Any possible key which isn't locally-used is unnecessary.
6834
6835 - finalize_derived_keys() re-organizes the possible locally-used keys and
6836 unnecessary keys, and does needed updates to TABLEs' bitmaps.
6837
6838 @verbatim
6839 ! !!
6840 EEEEEEEEEEPPPPPPP---
6841 ^ s->first_unused_keys
6842 ^ s->keys
6843 @endverbatim
6844
6845 The locally-used keys become existing keys and are made visible to nonlocal
6846 references. The unnecessary keys are chopped.
6847
6848 @verbatim
6849 ! !!
6850 EEEEEEEEEEEE-----
6851 ^ s->first_unused_keys
6852 ^ s->keys
6853 @endverbatim
6854
6855 - After that, another query block can be optimized.
6856 - So, query block after query block, optimization phases grow the key_info
6857 array.
6858 - If a reference is considered constant in a query block and the Optimizer
6859 decides to evaluate it, this triggers materialization (creation in engine),
6860 which freezes the key definition: other query blocks will not be allowed to
6861 add keys.
6862
6863 @retval true OOM
6864 @retval false otherwise
6865 */
6866
